{
  "According to the kinetic theory of matter, all particles of matter are __________.": "",
  "perfectly still at all times": "",
  "constantly in motion at all times": "",
  "motionless unless heated above 100 C": "",
  "only moving in the gaseous state": "",
  "The kinetic theory of matter states that all particles of matter are in constant motion, regardless of the state of matter. Even solid particles vibrate in place.": "",
  "As temperature increases, what happens to the speed of particles?": "",
  "The particles slow down as they absorb energy": "",
  "The particles stop moving and become frozen": "",
  "The particles speed up as they gain more energy": "",
  "The speed of the particles remains the same": "",
  "When temperature increases, particles gain kinetic energy and move faster. Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of particles.": "",
  "In which state of matter do particles have the most kinetic energy?": "",
  "Solid": "",
  "Liquid": "",
  "Gas": "",
  "Crystal": "",
  "Gas particles move the fastest and have the most kinetic energy among the common states of matter. They move freely in all directions with high speeds.": "",
  "How do particles move in a solid?": "",
  "They flow freely past one another in all directions": "",
  "They vibrate in fixed positions but do not move around": "",
  "They fly rapidly in straight lines between collisions": "",
  "They do not move at all and have zero kinetic energy": "",
  "In a solid, particles are tightly packed and vibrate in fixed positions. They have kinetic energy but cannot move freely like particles in liquids or gases.": "",
  "What determines the state of matter a substance is in?": "",
  "Only the color and size of the particles inside the substance": "",
  "The kinetic energy and the forces between its particles": "",
  "Only the shape of the container holding the substance inside": "",
  "The chemical formula written for the substance on the label": "",
  "The state of matter depends on the balance between the kinetic energy of particles (how fast they move) and the attractive forces between them (how strongly they are held together).": "",
  "In which state do particles move freely and fill the entire container?": "",
  "Solid only": "",
  "Liquid only": "",
  "Gas state": "",
  "All states": "",
  "Gas particles have enough kinetic energy to overcome the attractive forces between them. They spread out and fill whatever container they are in.": "",
  "What happens to the space between particles as a substance changes from solid to liquid to gas?": "",
  "The space between particles decreases with each change": "",
  "The space between particles increases with each change": "",
  "The space between particles always stays exactly the same": "",
  "The space between particles first increases then decreases": "",
  "As substances change from solid to liquid to gas, particles gain energy and move farther apart. Gases have the most space between particles.": "",
  "According to kinetic theory, why do gases expand to fill their container?": "",
  "Gas particles are attracted to the walls of the container strongly": "",
  "Gas particles move fast and spread out in all available directions": "",
  "Gases are pushed outward by the heavier air particles nearby": "",
  "Gravity pulls gas particles to every surface of the container wall": "",
  "Gas particles have high kinetic energy and weak attractive forces between them, so they move rapidly in all directions and spread out to fill any available space.": "",
