  "They are locked in fixed positions and can only vibrate": "",
  "They move freely in all directions like gas particles do": "",
  "They slide past each other while staying relatively close": "",
  "They have no kinetic energy and remain completely still": "",
  "Liquid particles have enough energy to slide past one another but not enough to completely break free from neighboring particles. This is why liquids flow but maintain a definite volume.": "",
  "Why does a solid have a definite shape according to kinetic theory?": "",
  "Its particles move so fast they push against each other equally": "",
  "Its particles have no energy and cannot move at all in any way": "",
  "Its particles vibrate in fixed positions held by strong forces": "",
  "Its particles are all the same size so they stack up neatly": "",
  "In a solid, strong attractive forces hold particles in fixed positions where they can only vibrate. This rigid arrangement gives solids their definite shape.": "",
  "What is the kinetic theory of matter?": "",
  "The theory that all particles of matter are in constant motion and their energy determines the state of matter": "",
  "The theory that only gas particles are in motion while solid and liquid particles are completely still": "",
  "The theory that matter can be created and destroyed during chemical reactions inside a laboratory": "",
  "The theory that all matter is made up of elements that are listed in the periodic table of elements": "",
  "The kinetic theory of matter states that all matter is made of particles that are in constant motion. The speed of the particles and the forces between them determine the state of matter.": "",
  "What is kinetic energy in the context of particle motion?": "",
  "The energy particles have because they are in motion": "",
  "The energy stored in the bonds between atoms in a molecule": "",
  "The energy needed to change a substance from one state to next": "",
  "The energy released when a chemical reaction takes place now": "",
  "Kinetic energy is the energy of motion. Every moving particle has kinetic energy, and faster-moving particles have more kinetic energy.": "",
  "What does 'intermolecular forces' mean?": "",
  "The forces of attraction between separate particles or molecules": "",
  "The bonds that hold atoms together within a single molecule unit": "",
  "The gravitational pull between the Earth and all matter on it": "",
  "The pressure exerted by gas particles against container walls": "",
  "Intermolecular forces are the attractive forces that exist between separate molecules or particles. They influence whether a substance is a solid, liquid, or gas.": "",
