  "The random, zigzag movement of tiny particles caused by collisions with surrounding molecules": "",
  "The organized circular flow of heated fluid moving upward and cooler fluid moving downward": "",
  "The transfer of heat energy through electromagnetic waves traveling through empty space": "",
  "The process by which a solid turns directly into a gas without first becoming a liquid state": "",
  "Brownian motion is the random, zigzag movement of small particles (like pollen in water) caused by constant bombardment from surrounding molecules. It provides evidence for the kinetic theory.": "",
  "What does 'diffusion' mean?": "",
  "The freezing of a liquid into a solid structure": "",
  "The spreading of particles from high to low concentration": "",
  "The vibration of particles in a fixed solid position": "",
  "The compression of gas into a smaller container space": "",
  "Diffusion is the process where particles spread out from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration due to their constant random motion.": "",
  "What does 'state of matter' mean?": "",
  "The chemical formula that represents a particular pure substance": "",
  "The physical form of matter determined by particle arrangement and motion": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance begins to boil and evaporate away": "",
  "The weight of a substance measured in grams on a laboratory balance": "",
  "A state of matter is a distinct physical form — solid, liquid, or gas — determined by how particles are arranged and how much kinetic energy they have.": "",
  "What does 'particle model' mean?": "",
  "A scientific model that explains matter as being made of tiny moving particles": "",
  "A physical replica of an atom built from clay or plastic for display purposes": "",
  "A mathematical equation that calculates the mass of a chemical compound": "",
  "A type of microscope used to view individual atoms on a smooth surface": "",
  "The particle model is a scientific model that represents all matter as being composed of tiny particles that are always moving. It helps explain the behavior of solids, liquids, and gases.": "",
  "What does 'phase change' mean?": "",
  "When a substance transforms from one state of matter to another": "",
  "When a substance changes its chemical identity during a reaction": "",
  "When particles are created from energy during a nuclear process": "",
  "When a gas is compressed until it becomes a completely new element": "",
  "A phase change is when a substance changes from one state of matter to another, such as melting (solid to liquid), boiling (liquid to gas), or freezing (liquid to solid).": "",
  "You open a bottle of perfume on one side of a room and soon people on the other side can smell it. What kinetic theory concept explains this?": "",
  "Condensation, because the perfume vapor turns back into liquid droplets in air": "",
  "Diffusion, because the perfume particles spread out through the air by moving randomly": "",
  "Freezing, because the perfume particles slow down as they travel across the entire room": "",
  "Filtration, because the air filters the perfume particles and carries them to the far side": "",
  "Diffusion explains this. The perfume molecules are in constant random motion and spread from the area of high concentration (the bottle) to lower concentration (across the room).": "",
  "A student notices that a drop of food coloring spreads faster in hot water than in cold water. How does kinetic theory explain this?": "",
  "Hot water is less dense, which makes the food coloring float and spread on top": "",
  "Cold water particles are frozen still, so they block the food coloring completely": "",
  "Particles in hot water move faster, which speeds up the diffusion of the coloring": "",
  "The food coloring reacts chemically with hot water but not with the cold water": "",
  "Higher temperature means particles have more kinetic energy and move faster. The faster-moving water particles collide with the food coloring more frequently, spreading it more quickly.": "",
